{{Infobox prepared food | name = ''Boerenjongens'' | image = Boerenjongens.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = [[Pancake]] served with ''boerenjongens'' | alternate_name = | country = [[Netherlands]] | region = | creator = | course = | type = | served = | main_ingredient = [[Raisin]]s, [[brandy]] | variations = ''[[Boerenmeisjes]]'' | calories = | other = }}
'''''Boerenjongens''''' ({{IPA-nl|buːrə(n)ˈjɔŋə(n)s}}) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] dish of [[raisins]] soaked in [[brandy]]. The name means "farmer boys" in [[Dutch language|Dutch]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Van der Sijs|first=Nicoline|title=Cookies, coleslaw, & Stoops: The influence of Dutch on the North American Languages|year=2009|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|location=Amsterdam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qIsDdUSYJMIC&pg=PA121}}</ref> This recipe is especially popular with older [[Dutch people|Dutch]] people and traditionally consumed at holidays or birthdays. In the city of [[Groningen (city)|Groningen]] and other cities in the countryside like [[Enschede]] there is often boerenjongens-flavoured ice cream for sale.
In [[United States|America]], it is sometimes made with [[whiskey]] instead of brandy.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
A variation to this recipe, apricots in ''brandewijn'', is called ''[[boerenmeisjes]]'' ({{lang-en|farmer girls}}).
