'''Essex South West''' was a [[European Parliament constituency|constituency]] of the [[European Parliament]] located in the [[United Kingdom]], electing one [[Member of the European Parliament]] by the [[first-past-the-post]] electoral system. Created in [[European Parliament election, 1979 (United Kingdom)|1979]] for the first elections to the European Parliament, it was abolished in 1994 and succeeded by the constituencies of [[Essex West and Hertfordshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Essex West and Hertfordshire East]] and [[Essex South (European Parliament constituency)|Essex South]].

==Boundaries==

On its creation in 1979, it consisted of the [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|parliamentary constituencies]] of [[Basildon (UK Parliament constituency)|Basildon]], [[Brentwood and Ongar (UK Parliament constituency)|Brentwood and Ongar]], [[Chelmsford (UK Parliament constituency)|Chelmsford]], [[Epping Forest (UK Parliament constituency)|Epping Forest]], [[Harlow (UK Parliament constituency)|Harlow]] and [[Thurrock (UK Parliament constituency)|Thurrock]].<ref>[[Boundary Commission for England]], ''European Assembly Constituencies'', December 1978.</ref>

After the 1984 boundary changes based on the new UK parliamentary constituencies created in 1983, it consisted of Basildon, [[Billericay (UK Parliament constituency)|Billericay]], Brentwood and Ongar, [[Castle Point (UK Parliament constituency)|Castle Point]], Chelmsford, Epping Forest, Harlow and Thurrock.<ref>European Parliament Information Office, ''MEPs and their constituencies'', December 1988</ref>

The constituency was abolished in 1994. Brentwood and Ongar, Chelmsford, Epping Forest and Harlow became part of [[Essex West and Hertfordshire East (European Parliament constituency)|Essex West and Hertfordshire East]]. Basildon, Billericay, Castle Point and Thurrock were now part of the new constituency of [[Essex South (European Parliament constituency)|Essex South]].<ref>''The European Parliament 1994-1999 : MEPs and European constituencies in the United Kingdom'', London : UK Office of the European Parliament, November 1994.</ref>

