{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name= Estonian Space Office |logo= Estonian_Space_Office_logo.jpg |logo_width= |logo_caption= |formed= |preceding1= |jurisdiction= [[Government of Estonia]] |headquarters= [[Tallinn]], [[Estonia]] |employees= |chief1_name= Madis Võõras |chief1_position= Sectoral Manager (within ''Enterprise Estonia'') |website= {{URL|eas.ee/kosmos}} }}
The '''Estonian Space Office''' ('''ESO'''; {{lang-et|'''Eesti Kosmosebüroo'''}}) is the unit established within {{Interlanguage link multi|Enterprise Estonia|et|3=Ettevõtluse Arendamise Sihtasutus}} by the [[Government of Estonia]] to facilitate membership in the [[European Space Agency]] and related commercial and research ties. In addition ESO serves as a contact point with the [[International Astronautical Federation|IAF]], [[European Association for the International Space Year|EURISY]] and [[European Organisation for the Exploitation of Meteorological Satellites|EUMETSAT]] in procurement-related matters.<ref>{{cite web | title = About the Space Office | url = http://www.eas.ee/kosmos/en/estonian-space-office/about-the-space-office |work = eas.ee | publisher = EAS | accessdate = 14 December 2015}}</ref>
ESO is not a [[space agency]]. State space policy as it exists is managed through the Space Affairs Council at the [[Ministry of Economic Affairs and Communications]]. ESO functions as a centre for technology and business competence alongside [[Tartu Observatory]] which has responsibility for space science, space exploration and remote sensing. Various activities within the [[Framework Programmes for Research and Technological Development]] of the European Union for education, science and innovation, including funding for space programs, are coordinated by the [[Archimedes Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Estonian Space Governance System and Activities Today | url = http://www.eas.ee/kosmos/en/estonia-and-space/estonian-space-governance-system |work = eas.ee | publisher = EAS | accessdate = 14 December 2015}}</ref>
Since 2010, the [[Riigikogu]] has had a 'Space Studies Support Group' (''Kosmose valdkonna toetusrühm'') currently chaired by [[Anne Sulling]].
