{{Infobox network | name =The Voice of Mongolia | logo = | country = [[Mongolia]] | network_type = [[Radio network]] | available = International | owner = [[Mongol HD Television]] | language = [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]], [[English language|English]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] | key_people = | launch_date = | past_names = | website = |}}
'''Voice of Mongolia''' is the official [[international broadcasting]] station of [[Mongolia]].
The Voice Of Mongolia is the country's only overseas broadcasting service and is operated by [[Mongol HD Television]], a private service broadcaster. Short-wave international broadcasting in [[Mongolia]] dates back over 40 years. The first broadcast in October, 1964 was a half hour transmission in [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]] and [[Chinese language|Chinese]], beamed to [[China]]. In the next few years, Mongolian international broadcasting expanded in terms of languages used, broadcast hours and target areas. The English service of Radio Ulaanbaatar, which was renamed The Voice Of Mongolia on January 1, 1997, was launched on January 29, 1965. Today the output of The Voice Of Mongolia consists of various programmes designed to provide information about [[Mongolia]] and the Mongolians, their history, traditions and culture. It broadcasts a total of 8 hours a day in 5 languages: [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]], [[English language|English]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Japanese language|Japanese]].
==Current broadcasts== All of the Voice Of Mongolia's broadcasts come directly from its [[Khonkhor Transmitting Station]], about 25&nbsp;km east of [[Ulan Bator]], Mongolia's capital. It broadcasts through Soviet-made 100, 250, and 500&nbsp;kW transmitters and curtain antennas built in the mid sixties. The transmissions beamed to East Asia provide fair reception in South America, and the South Asian transmissions can be heard in Southern Africa and in Europe as well. However, this reception is influenced by propagation conditions and frequency congestion.
